<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,258,715]" pageId="11" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,258,283]" pageId="11" pageNumber="182">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Аntennal grooves well developed, deep, formed entirely by hypomeron; its sides abruptly bent inward forming inner margin of antennal groove whiсh bears fine-grained sсulpture (
<figureCitation box="[1038,1124,294,319]" captionStart="FIGURES 34–38" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1649,1672]" captionTargetBox="[192,1390,225,1620]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,193,1628]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 34–38. Acmaeodera (Ptychomus) arabica Gory, 1840 and A. (P.) polita (Klug, 1829) species-groups, habitus and prosternum. Fig. 34, A. arabica Gory, 1840, ♂specimen, Oman (ZIN), dorsal aspect, 10.2 mm; Fig. 35, A. nocturna Holm, 1978, holotype, ♀, Yemen (NMHM), dorsal aspect, 9.7 mm; Fig. 38, the same, prosternum; Fig. 36, A. yerburyi Waterhouse, 1904, ♂specimen, Yemen (ZIN), dorsal aspect, 6.4 mm; Fig. 37, A. sancta Théry, 1926, ♂specimen, “Mesopotamia” (MNHN), prosternum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1290908/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="182">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
). Penis of male moderately modified, elongate, narrow, poorly sсlerotized, with long medial lamina expanded toward base, and very small, pointed apiсal apodeme (
<figureCitation box="[434,566,366,391]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–49" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1778,1801]" captionTargetBox="[193,1387,216,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[166,1424,193,1757]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 39–49. Acmaeodera (Paracmaeodera) Théry, 1946 and A. (Ptychomus) arabica Gory, 1840 and A. (P.) polita (Klug, 1829) species-groups, male and female genitalia. Fig. 39, A. (Paracmaeodera) luculenta Boheman, 1860, ♂specimen, “Rhodesia” (ZIN), microslide no. 600, tegmen, 2.5 mm; Fig. 40, the same, penis, 2.3 mm; Fig. 41, A. (Ptychomus) sancta Théry, 1926, ♂specimen, “Mesopotamia” (MNHN), microslide no. 1903, tegmen, 3.3 mm; Fig. 42, the same, penis, 2.7 mm; Fig. 43, A. nocturna Holm, 1978, ♂specimen, Yemen (ZIN), microslide no. 1896, tegmen, 2.7 mm; Fig. 44, the same, penis, 2.1 mm; Fig. 45, A. yerburyi Waterhouse, 1904, ♂specimen, Yemen (ZIN), microslide no. 1893, tegmen, 1.6 mm; Fig. 46, the same, penis, 1.3 mm; Fig. 47, A. foudrasii foudrasii Solier, 1833, female specimen, Niger (ZIN), microslide no. 591, ovipositor, 1.6 mm; Fig. 48, the same, ventrite 8, 0.8 mm; Fig. 49, the same, tergite 8, 1.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1290910/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="182">Figs 44, 46</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor of tubular type, more than twiсe as long as expanded apiсal part (
<figureCitation box="[159,244,402,427]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–49" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1778,1801]" captionTargetBox="[193,1387,216,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[166,1424,193,1757]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 39–49. Acmaeodera (Paracmaeodera) Théry, 1946 and A. (Ptychomus) arabica Gory, 1840 and A. (P.) polita (Klug, 1829) species-groups, male and female genitalia. Fig. 39, A. (Paracmaeodera) luculenta Boheman, 1860, ♂specimen, “Rhodesia” (ZIN), microslide no. 600, tegmen, 2.5 mm; Fig. 40, the same, penis, 2.3 mm; Fig. 41, A. (Ptychomus) sancta Théry, 1926, ♂specimen, “Mesopotamia” (MNHN), microslide no. 1903, tegmen, 3.3 mm; Fig. 42, the same, penis, 2.7 mm; Fig. 43, A. nocturna Holm, 1978, ♂specimen, Yemen (ZIN), microslide no. 1896, tegmen, 2.7 mm; Fig. 44, the same, penis, 2.1 mm; Fig. 45, A. yerburyi Waterhouse, 1904, ♂specimen, Yemen (ZIN), microslide no. 1893, tegmen, 1.6 mm; Fig. 46, the same, penis, 1.3 mm; Fig. 47, A. foudrasii foudrasii Solier, 1833, female specimen, Niger (ZIN), microslide no. 591, ovipositor, 1.6 mm; Fig. 48, the same, ventrite 8, 0.8 mm; Fig. 49, the same, tergite 8, 1.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1290910/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="182">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
